Ask HN: What do you do to start and develop friendships?
text: I've been reading Never Eat Alone by Keith Ferrazzi, which is about the importance of networking and developing lasting relationships, and Keith does talk about preparation (get to know a person before you meet them), about being genuine, about having something to offer, about the importance of being liked, but I think I'm missing something a bit more fundamental. While I cherish relationships I do build, developing a genuine human bond is somewhat of a mystery to me: it happens sometimes, but infrequently, and doesn't seem to be under my control at all.

Tell HN: Paul’s law”: the computer you really want is $5k
text:
My brother Paul back in the early 1990’s once said “the computer you really want is always $5,000”.

This has held remarkably true for 35 years. Sure you can invalid it easily by saying you want a Cray XMP or a fancy Apple or whatever but fact is for consumer machines, the computer you really want - a really nice fast machine at the high end of the consumer range - has been about $5,000 for a long time, and remains true.

It was even true through the mid to late 70s and 80s.

Ask HN: Starting a startup with a sibling: how to not destroy our relationship?
text:
I am planning to co-found a startup with my brother. We will be bootstrapping. The business is not capital intensive.

I heard of enough stories how relatives or close friends lose the relationship due to some quarrel in the business. Which questions should we ask (and answer!) ourselves before we endeavor into this? First and foremost, we want to avoid situations that can be avoided that can lead into an irreversible conflict.

Both anecdotes (I did X and it caused Y, and it was great/awful) and general advice would be appreciated.

Thank you!
